    "body": "### Problem\r\n\r\nInvoking `nvim_set_hl_ns` with anything but 0 makes `style=minimal` floating windows ignore the NormalFloat background color and instead become transparent:\r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/user-attachments/assets/c5c7949a-5971-4287-9dc1-6badef498215\r\n\r\nIs this what it's meant to do? Seems not.\r\n\r\n### Steps to reproduce\r\n\r\n1. `nvim --clean`\r\n2. `:hi NormalFloat guibg=#ff0000` (make it easier to see, NormalFloat is only a slightly different shade than Normal in the default colorscheme)\r\n3. `:lua vim.api.nvim_open_win(0, false, {relative='win', row=3, col=3, width=12, height=3, style='minimal'})`\r\n4. `:lua vim.api.nvim_set_hl_ns(vim.api.nvim_create_namespace(\"test1\"))`\r\n\r\n### Expected behavior\r\n\r\nI'd expect the float to stay red, as the new namespace doesn't specify any highlightsâ€”I'd expect no changes whatsoever anywhere.\r\n\r\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\r\n\r\nv0.11.0-dev-711+g7b7c95dac (reproducible with v0.10.1 and v0.9.5 as well)\r\n\r\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\r\n\r\nN/A (nvim api specific issue)\r\n\r\n### Operating system/version\r\n\r\nDebian testing\r\n\r\n### Terminal name/version\r\n\r\nalacritty 0.13.2 (reproducible with rxvt-unicode 9.31 as well)\r\n\r\n### $TERM environment variable\r\n\r\nalacritty (or rxvt-unicode-256color)\r\n\r\n### Installation\r\n\r\nnvim-linux64.tar.gz from latest GitHub nightly",
